Textbook: Page 416, Question 9*, parts (a) through (g), (k), and (l). (using R)

For part (l), make sure to use model.matrix() to compare the design matrix from lm() with the corresponding matrix of part (a). a. The null hypothesis is that beta1 through beta6 all equal 0. That is, that there is no correlation between any of these variables and the average SO2 concentration in each city. The alternative hypothesis is that at least one of the beta.hats are not equal to 0. H0:1 = 2 = 3 = 4 = 5 = 6 = 0 HA: not all k equal 0.

Applied*:

You perform an experiment measuring the response of a certain cellular metabolite concentration in cell cultures after a certain drug is added at increasing concentrations. The data are in the file regression.tsv. Plot the data. What kind of plot is this? Perform an appropriate linear regression. What is the best fitting line equation? Show this on the plot. Check the linear model assumptions using diagnostic plots. Analyze the result of the model fit and report your conclusions.

regression<-read.csv(file="regression.tsv", sep="\t")

It looks like data point 9 is very important for the model based on the Cooks distance, but it seems like an outlier compared to the rest of the data points. I will try to re-run the linear regression removing observation 9. On the Residuals vs Fitted chart, it looks roughly like y=0 except near the middle, but that may be fine. The Normal Q-Q chart looks roughtly like a straight line, which is good. The Scale-Location chart shows no clear trend, which is also good.
